1f43d3d4c6d96c26d6777518d49160dd, depends what you're trying to use it for microdata is useful when you want to share data with 3rd parties via a shared vocabulary. data-* is useful if you just want extra metadata for your own scripts to use internally on the page. yes, it can be, depending on what use cases and problems your trying to solve. you could just use class="title" that's not a goal, that's a specific solution for achieving some other goal. you could just as easily use document.querySelectorAll("[data-title]"); or .querySelectorAll(".title"); ok, so then you have a requriement for obtaining easily scriptable and structured data from your page?

is anyone actually taking that seriously? heh drm being fundamentally and irreconcilably incompatible with open source browsers, apis specifically to support pieces of it seem completely useless (unless browsers become less open, and anything encouraging that is bad) i've worked on drm :( (but for turnkey arcade systems, not consumer stuff) (and given that the underlying game engine was, for the most part, released open source, I can live with that) $5000+ machines aren't consumer products, no matter who ends up buying them in the end different scale of product :) consumer games are $50, not $5000 also vastly different scale (we'd have been happy to sell a thousand units) i know all the arguments; at least in that case (the one I happen to have direct experience with), the practicalities had to come before principle because the variables don't work out that way there are plenty of people who would pirate our game if it was easy to do (just a new HDD), but nobody with the expertese to break it was actually trying versions of our game where the encryption was broken sold significantly less than the ones where it wasn't (don't have exact numbers, probably couldn't say them if I did) also, enforcing copyright internationally takes a lot more resources than domestically then we'd need our own legal defense team. heh when the lack of DRM means there will be no future product, they can it definitely was in our case (i'm not saying it is in *all* cases) what? (i know the cost to us in implementing the drm, since i did it all myself--took 3-4 weeks) as far as I know it was never broken so long as I worked there, at least (at least based on the fact that bootlegs didn't show up in the wild) (forget how long; well over a year) that was a much older system (written maybe 6-7 years earlier) it was much weaker and used on too many products without changing 3-4 weeks initially; that system was used on two products while I was there we actually did have a system for in-place upgrades; the market wasn't really set up to use it, so we didn't make much use of it (insert USB drive with upgrade, push button, wait a minute) the market is always set up to copy games for free if they can (at least in some countries) that's for consumers buying games online; it doesn't translate to $500+ upgrade packs for arcade games (eg. many arcades can't get internet access to machines) the market isn't prepared to pay anything whatsoever, if it can get stuff for $0 (or $30 or whatever the cost of a tiny HDD is) again, steam has no comparative value to arcade machines buying a song on iTunes is "push button, spend $1, get a song"; arcade owners don't spend hundreds of dollars on an upgrade on a one-click whim purchase it's completely different, because upgrading an arcade machine is a financial investment, buying a game on steam is not not in comparable notions of the word i buy a $40 game if I think I'll have $40 of fun with it; an arcade owner buys a $500 upgrade if he thinks he'll make $500 more money from coin drops as a result sounds unrelated to me our engine was almost all released as open-source, so I have no trouble sleeping at night :) http://sourceforge.net/projects/stepmania/

not to mention it being user-hostile i don't understand how any engineer who works on drm tech can live with themselves the vast majority of arcade machines i see these days are privately owned so it's still "consumer stuff" cars aren't consumer products? :-) houses aren't consumer products? :-) i don't see how my point is that if it's privately owned, the drm would stop someone from making private modifications to their property (and if it's not a consumer product, why bother with drm? a commercial competitor who is so beyond the law that the legal system is not a sufficient recourse is certainly not gonna have any trouble reverse-engineering some obfuscation) (in fact such a competitior is far more likely to just steal the code/assets/designs/whatever straight from the source repository than bother with buying an actual product) (just look at how movies get redistributed before they're even commercially available) and how many of those people actually bought copies instead? should've just paid for a security guard for each unit to stand there with a cane and beat anyone who tried to open the box, instead anyway the ends don't justify the means consumer or not better to have no products than to have drm, imho (luckily, that isn't even close to the actual result of not having drm) i'm skeptical, but i don't have all the data so can't comment one way or the other on your specific case generally when i've seen people make those claims though they tend to forget to account for all the factors, e.g. the opportunity cost of working on drm 3-4 weeks total, or 3-4 weeks on the ones that got broken, or 3-4 weeks on one game that didn't get broken?L i thought you just said "versions of our game where the encryption was broken sold significantly less than the ones where it wasn't" so 3-4 weeks per game then how much more would you have made if you'd spent those 3-4 weeks e.g. working on a system where they could buy the disks to put new games in for very little instead of requiring that they buy an entirely new unit? (i'm guessing as to the mechanics here since i don't know what you did exactly) but the market was set up to do it without you if they broke the drm? not at all, e.g. valve has found that by making buying games actually easier than copying them, they sell more games than they would if they had drm so maybe the problem isn't that your market isn't set up for it but that you were charging rates the market wasn't ready to support without using artifical tactics like drm again, valve has shown that to not be true iTunes has also shown that to not be true (for music) i see no reason to believe that any particular market would be any mare special than another here again, maybe the problem is that you were charging too much to make it sustainable all purchases boil down to investments when you buy a game on steam, you're return is going to be in entertainment per hour instead of dollars per hour but at the end of the day, what are dollars if not a way to get entertainment? sounds the same to me whatever lets you sleep at night :-)

7f9405da4034bf43083e64b57302a8e6, just because openness and standards work for the web doesn't mean they're needed everywhere.  I tend to broadly agree with Eric S. Raymond's analysis of open-source software, where he suggests that closed-source software will always work better in some markets.  The same logic applies to open standards. Well, if interoperability is useful, yes.  What do games need to interoperate on? A typical high-end game is a standalone product that interacts with no other program (beyond the OS) and is basically obsolete in two years. What exactly is there to standardize? What sort of API would they expose?  Different games work very differently, that's one of the problems. I don't think standardization would help with that. Standardization is needed for inter-program APIs, document formats, things like that.  But any two independent games are different enough that there's nothing I can see that they could usefully share, in general. Well, they share things like graphics engines, clearly. But not along nice clean standardizable lines that you could make a stable API out of. At least it's my impression that when games use a third-party engine, they typically customize it to fit their needs. Well, yes.  Also file access can be standardized. Novel idea right there. But that's standardizing the OS, not the game. Essentially, yes. (I've given thought to the possibility that an open-source graphics engine for games could be successful, if it used a dual-licensing scheme in the vein of MySQL.) (It's really ridiculous how companies rewrite their graphics engines from scratch for most games they make.) 7f9405da4034bf43083e64b57302a8e6, even similar games aren't similar enough that I see any useful API you could make. Maybe adopting a common scripting language or something like that, sure. Would be possible. But high-end games are usually written from scratch in a very short period and then thrown out.  That makes it unattractive to invest in features that aren't broadly useful. ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, I've never heard of Ogre.  I'm just saying it could work, it could also fail for lots of reasons. My strategy would be to distribute it for free and let small players use it for free, and figure that if any big games stole it we'd notice. Try to get universities to use it in their courses, try to get a development community going. Anyway, I'm not actually going to try this, just an idle thought. hsivonen, you are aware that the chairs will consider objections even if they don't use the words "I object" every two sentences, right? Ah, interesting. Where do they get their development money from, if they're MIT-licensed?  Contracts, support?  I thought good 3D engines required very large ongoing development costs. (As opposed to most open-source projects, which can be more or less completed and then add features at their leisure without necessarily falling far behind) b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, that I agree with. And it's still competitive?  Or it's not competitive with the commercial engines, but it's good enough for the cost? b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, on which issue? b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, I hate when people refer to issues by numbers.  Can't you at least use the short description? Is that the RDFa prefix one? I suspect that one's a lost cause politically, but the chairs may surprise me. What does "a single light source" mean, in practice? Ah. So constant illumination from a fixed direction. I find graphics vaguely interesting. I remember being amused when I saw in my brother's 3D graphics program (3DS Max or whatever) that he could change the rate at which the intensity of light dropped off. Constant, inverse-square, inverse, inverse-cube, exponential . . . Granted, constant makes sense for very far light sources like the sun, but exponential dropoff for light?  I guess you're not always aiming for realism, in graphics. The software also supported indices of refraction less than 1. Although negative indices of refraction can be possible. b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, I don't think the chairs have dropped any objections lately just because of how they were phrased, did they? ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, do you know of any book I could read that would teach me more about the principles of graphics programming, without expecting that I'd be willing to write any actual code except maybe really trivial snippets? I would like to get it, read the first twenty pages, put it aside somewhere, and forget about it for months until I clean up my room, at which point I'll realize I have no time to read it and put it on my shelf, with a forlorn bookmark forever remaining in it as a testament to my lack of persistence. b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea, that objection was ignored because it suggested a change that wasn't suggested by any change proposal. Not in an actual working computer, needless to say. Wasn't GeForce 1 a PCI card, though?  If so, maybe it would still work.  I bet the Linux kernel still supports it. if we have </li</ul>, we start from http://www.w3.org/TR/html5/tokenization.html#end-tag-open-state , 'l' is a latin small letter, so we move on to "tag name state", we follow that and consume the  i and the < as part of the tag name, but then there's a /, and that apparently means "Switch to the self-closing start tag state." isn't this wrong considering that </li is already an end tag? so in this case if I go to the "self-closing start tag state" I see 3 options, if there's a > I will emit what I got so far (as an end tag), if not I keep moving on so in this case I should go back and keep consuming till ul, and then emit 'li</ul', right? "self-closing tag state" is a bit better but afaiu there's nothing self-closing here where "here" would be e.g. </li/> or </li</>ul> if it's not followed by > so with </li</ul> I should emit a closing 'li</' and discard an 'ul' attribute, right? indeed makes sense s/makes sense/sounds like a correct interpretation of the standard/ what's "LIU00003C" ? U00003C == <? why that weird notation? why not LI\x3C or LI\u003c? does createElement even recognize U00003C as <? actually "LI\x3C" should be exactly the same as "LI<" it's the first time I see this notation

I think it's just the state name that's misleading (Maybe "self-closing tag state" would be clearer) "self-closing start tag or bogus end tag that looks quite like a self-closing start tag state" From self-closing start tag state, it says to reconsume the "/" in before attribute name state Oops, not "/" In self-closing start tag state it will see the "u" next, and reconsume that in before attribute name state which will make it create an attribute named "ul" The tag name will be "li<", because the tag name state does not append the "/" to the tag name ("l" appends, "i" appends, "<" appends, "/" causes switch to self-closing state, "u" gets reconsumed in before attribute name state, "u" starts attribute name, "l" appends, ">" ends tag, I think) Really? Something must be wrong HTML should never make sense :-p Matches the output of http://livedom.validator.nu/?%3C!DOCTYPE%20html%3E%0D%0A%3Cli%3C%2Ful%3E too Yes document.createElement("li<") is not allowed (and that DOM viewer uses createElement) You probably can't have "\" either No, it's just a relatively unambiguous way to represent the name without making createElement throw exceptions (Also it matches http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/the-end.html#coercing-an-html-dom-into-an-infoset ) I don't know if anyone in the world other than hsivonen uses that notation

Maybe that is UA dependent thing s/those/though/ 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: still, what in the spec explains that the previous top level page should load latest iframe document? the draft doesn't really say anything about what should happen to sub-browsing contexts when previous top level page is loaded 042dd99eb0ff8653814e445ca0093427: yeah, at least gecko finds the document from caller and uses that as owner document 042dd99eb0ff8653814e445ca0093427: I don't think that is supported 042dd99eb0ff8653814e445ca0093427: calling the constructor fails boots a windows machine 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: but the go(-3) goes to the startpage in my testcase and still, where does the draft say what the iframes should load when going back in top level page? that is easy that is why I disable bfcache at least for gecko but without bfcache (btw, do all the browsers have something like? maybe chrome doesn't, at least its back-forward is slower than in other browsers) and how can the browser know which iframe loads which page? gecko has a tree of browsing contexts or tree of session histories but the way it is implemented doesn't work well with dynamic iframe additions/removals it tries to map session history tree to browsing context tree and with dynamic iframe additions/removals that isn't always right ...and that is what I'm trying to fix but I'd like to fix it to do something which is actually spec'ed somewhere not sure. well, webkit's go() handling is already so strange that it is difficult to test but as a starting point I'd like to understand how go() should work and then figure out what to do with dynamic changes ok, I'll continue testing yeah, I haven't seen anything in IE8's behavior that I'm against at. looks like IE8 does what the spec says right? what IE8 does seems to have security advantages, though it does mean that for go(x) where |x| > 1 the back button doesn't match the API dunno if that's a problem bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: hold on, minor cat emergency bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: ok back bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: assuming we do go with the IE8 model, then a literal reading of the spec would mean that when you go back, you just end up in whatever state you happened to last be when that top-level browsing context last had that document active bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: which means that if you were to go to A-2, then fast-forward to B-2, then go(-2), you should end up at A-2 again bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: even though going go(+1) from there would take you to A-3 bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: and then going go(+1) again would take you to B-2, not B-1 i guess we should see what IE does with those cases bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: can you stick a javascript:go(-2) and a javascript:go(+1) to A-2, A-3, B-1, and B-2? woo, IE8 does do what i said for the first thing i described the go(-2) case where you navigated the history as i described and then clicking forward from A-2 goes to A-3, and from there goes to B-2 and clicking back there goes to B-1 not saying that's the most understandable UI but it does match what I'd expect the API to do per the spec right, it would because the subframes aren't in the joint history the subframes of the inactive documents, i mean well there are two possible cases: 1. bfcache is active, doc is in the cache: you just show it as it was, unchanged 2. doc was evicted from bfcache, and you have to refetch the document and rerender it and so forth: the iframes are considered "persisted user state" which the UA is allowed to resync i should probably spec that in more detail beats me how does firefox do it? the most obvious solution is to serialise the state of each frame's frames[] hierarchy and just walk down the tree as each one onloads, navigating its subframes accordingly but how does it map them to iframes? what do other UAs do? well the spec doesn't really say what to do with iframes when reloading a document evicted from the bfcache (or never stored in the first place) i'm more or less happy to spec anything you come up with, if it's sane and/or matches implementations and/or legacy content expectations for things in the bfcache, it seems the spec matches IE8, which is good so i'd like to standardise on that it seems to make sense and is relatively easy to describe well the back button and the go() API don't have to match, so you're welcome to make that work however you like

From the manual:  Another extension is supported by MySQL for optionally specifying the display width of an integer value in parentheses following the base keyword for the type (for example, INT(4)). This optional display width specification is used to left-pad the display of values having a width less than the width specified for the column. The display width does not constrain the range of values that can be stored in the column, nor the number of digits that are displayed for values having a width exceeding that specified for the column.
